Peel and very finely dice the @carrot{1/2}(peeled and finely diced), @garlic clove{1}(peeled and finely diced) and @red onion{1/3}(peeled and finely diced). Peel and roughly chop (1cm cubes) the @parsnip{1}(peeled and chopped into 1cm cubes). Slice the sides from the @swede{1}(peeled and chopped into 1cm cubes) to make a square then chop it into 1cm cubes. Roughly chop the @dried apricots{3}(roughly chopped).

Heat @olive oil{1%tbsp} in a #non-stick pan{} on medium-low heat. Cook the carrot, garlic and onion for about ~{6%minutes}.

> Tip: You want to cook the mixture until it is soft and be sure not to let it brown.

Now add the parsnip and swede. Sprinkle on @salt{1/4%tsp} with the @turmeric{1/2%tsp} and @allspice{1/2%tsp}. Add the chopped apricots, add @water{3%tbsp}, put a #lid{} on and stew for ~{5%minutes} more. When the veg has softened, add the @chopped tomatoes{1%400g can}, ½ the @vegetable stock pot{1} and @water{250%ml}.

Add the @ground cinnamon{1/2%tsp} and let it gently bubble away for ~{20-25%minutes} or until you have a thick stew.

While all that's happening slice the @cucumber{1/2}(sliced in half lengthways then seeded) in half lengthways then slice each half lengthways again and remove the seeds in the middle by sliding your knife under them. Chop the cucumber into tiny (less than 1cm) cubes (or grate it) then mix with the @Greek style yoghurt{1/2%cup} and a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{} to make tzatziki.

Boil @water{150%ml} with the other half of your @vegetable stock pot{1/2}. Add in the @couscous{100%g} and cover the #pot{} tightly. Take the pot off the heat and leave to rest for ~{5%minutes}.

> Tip: Be exact with the amount of water to prevent soggy couscous!

Roughly chop the @coriander{1/2%bunch}(roughly chopped) and stir through the stew at the last minute. Fluff up the couscous with a #fork{}. Serve the stew on top of the couscous with a sprinkle of the @flaked almonds{2%tbsp} and some tzatziki.